{"title_page": "Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n| name                    = Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet\n| native_name             = \n| native_name_lang        = <!-- ISO 639-2 code e.g. \"fr\" for French. If more than one, use {{lang}} instead -->\n| settlement_type         = Subdistrict of Stockholm\n| image_skyline           = Skarpnack allee 2.jpg\n| image_alt               = Skarpn\u00e4cks All\u00e9\n| image_caption           = Skarpn\u00e4cks All\u00e9\n| image_flag              = \n| flag_alt                = \n| image_seal              = \n| seal_alt                = \n| image_shield            = \n| shield_alt              = \n| nickname                = \n| motto                   = \n| image_map               = \n| map_alt                 = \n| map_caption             = \n| pushpin_map             =Sweden Stockholm Municipality\n| pushpin_label_position  = none\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_mapsize         = 250\n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location of Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet in [[Stockholm Municipality]]\n| coordinates             = {{coord|59|16|4.28|N|18|7|6.65|E|display=inline,title}}\n| coor_pinpoint           = \n| coordinates_footnotes   = \n| subdivision_type        = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = [[Sweden]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Provinces of Sweden|Province]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[S\u00f6dermanland]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[Counties of Sweden|County]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Stockholm County]]\n| subdivision_type3       = [[Municipalities of Sweden|Municipality]]\n| subdivision_name3       = [[Stockholm Municipality]]\n| subdivision_type4       = [[Boroughs of Stockholm|Borough]]\n| subdivision_name4       = [[Skarpn\u00e4ck borough]]\n| subdivision_type5       = [[District]]\n| subdivision_name5       = [[Skarpn\u00e4cks g\u00e5rd]]\n| established_title       = \n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| seat_type               = \n| seat                    = \n| government_footnotes    = \n| leader_party            = \n| leader_title            = \n| leader_name             = \n| unit_pref               = Metric<!-- or US or UK -->\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = \n| area_land_km2           = \n| area_water_km2          = \n| area_water_percent      = \n| area_note               = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_footnotes    = <ref name=\"skarpnacksfaltet-stats\">{{cite web|title=Omr\u00e5desfakta delomr\u00e5de Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet|publisher=Stockholms stads utrednings- och statistikkontor AB|url=http://www.usk.stockholm.se/tabellverktyg/tv.aspx?projekt=omradesfakta&omrade=sp10|accessdate=2010-08-03}}</ref>\n| population_total        = 8,734\n| population_as_of        = December 31, 2009\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_note         = \n| timezone1               = \n| utc_offset1             = \n| timezone1_DST           = \n| utc_offset1_DST         = \n| postal_code_type        = \n| postal_code             = \n| area_code_type          = \n| area_code               = \n| iso_code                = \n| website                 = <!-- [http://www.example.com example.com] -->\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet''' ({{lang-en|The Skarpn\u00e4ck Field}}) is a subdistrict of [[Skarpn\u00e4cks G\u00e5rd]] in the [[Skarpn\u00e4ck borough]] of [[Stockholm]], [[Sweden]]. Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet was built in the 1980s, and has 8,734 inhabitants as of December 31, 2009.<ref name=\"skarpnacksfaltet-stats\" />\n\n== History ==\n[[Archaeology|Archaeological finding]]s, such as a [[hill fort]] and [[stone circle]]s near [[Flatensj\u00f6n]], indicate that Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet and nearby areas were populated by [[viking]]s as early as the 10th century.<ref name=\"historik-care\">{{cite web|title=Fr\u00e5n vikingatid till nutid - en liten historik|publisher=Skarpn\u00e4ck Care AB|url=http://www.segelflygaren.net/historik_skarp.pdf|access-date=2010-08-03|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724060544/http://www.segelflygaren.net/historik_skarp.pdf|archive-date=2011-07-24|df=}}</ref><ref name=\"skarpnack-book\">{{cite book |last= Roxell |first= Pia |author2=Eva Wernlid  |title= Skarpn\u00e4ck - Tegelstaden p\u00e5 f\u00e4ltet |publisher= Stockholmia F\u00f6rlag |year= 2009 |isbn= 978-91-7031-219-9}}</ref>\n\n=== Skarpa by ===\n[[Skarpa]], a [[cottage]] of the [[\u00c5rsta Castle|\u00c5rsta]] property, was first mentioned in the will of [[Valdemar, Duke of Finland|Duke Valdemar]] in 1318, where it was listed as one of his donations to [[Uppsala domkyrka]].<ref name=\"hembygd-skarpaby\">{{cite web|title=Skarpa by|publisher=Bagarmossens hembygdsf\u00f6rening|url=http://www.bagarmossen.org/skpnck/Skarpaby.asp|accessdate=2010-08-03}}</ref> Skarpa derives from the word ''skarp'' ({{lang-en|sharp}}), and is believed to have indicated the soil quality, which was heavy [[loam]].<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" /><ref name=\"hembygd-skarpaby\" /> It is believed that the small village of [[Skarpa by]], with the Skarpa cottage, also consisted of three [[homestead (buildings)|homestead]]s dating as far back as the 13th century.<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" />\n\n[[File:Skarpnacks gard 2008.jpg|left|thumb|The main building of Skarpn\u00e4cks g\u00e5rd, as constructed in the 1860s.]]\nAccording to a document from 1432, Skarpa was sold by the [[Archdiocese of Uppsala]] to Hans Kr\u00f6pelin, the chieftain of [[Eric of Pomerania]], who was the [[King of Sweden]] at the time.<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" /> Like in the will of Duke Valdemar, Skarpa was part of the \u00c5rsta property.<ref name=\"historik-care\" /><ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" />\n\nDuring the 17th century, the land and cottages of Skarpa by were included in the [[Tyres\u00f6]] property. Tyres\u00f6 was owned by the [[Oxenstierna]] family, which constructed a mansion in Skarpa by. A countess of the family (Maria Sofia de la Gardie<ref name=\"historik-care\" />) made Skarpa a manor ({{lang-sv|s\u00e4teri}}) which she named ''Skarpn\u00e4ck''.<ref name=\"historik-care\" /><ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" /> The manor continued to grow in the 18th century, now housing workers and farmers. The manor switched owners a few times, and in the beginning of the 19th century, there were almost 30 buildings in Skarpn\u00e4cks g\u00e5rd.<ref name=\"historik-care\" /><ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" /> The last owner, Friedrich Neum\u00fcller, constructed the main building which still exists today, roughly 150 years later.<ref name=\"historik-care\" /> Eventually, in 1922, the property was sold to the Stockholm Municipality.<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" />\n\n=== Skarpn\u00e4ck Airfield ===\n[[File:Segelflyg Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet maj 1972.jpg|left|thumb|Sailplane at Skarpn\u00e4ck in 1972.]]\nThe [[Skarpn\u00e4ck Airfield]] was constructed on Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet around 1940.<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" /> Originally intended to be a reserve airfield for the [[Swedish military|military]], those plans were soon abandoned, and in 1943, ''Stockholms Segelflygklubb'' ({{lang-en|Stockholm's Sailplane Association}}) moved its operations to the airfield.<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" /><ref name=\"ssfk\">{{cite web|title=Om klubben|publisher=Stockholms Segelflygklubb|url=http://www4.idrottonline.se/templates/Page.aspx?id=378185|accessdate=2010-08-03}}</ref> The airfield was commonly used for other activities, including balloon flying, races such as the [[1948 Stockholm Grand Prix]], baseball and [[greyhound racing]].<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" />\n\nThe airfield became a centre for [[Counterculture|alternative society movements]].<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" /> In August 1950, the [[International Union of Socialist Youth]], together with the [[Swedish Social Democratic Youth Association]], organized a week-long international tent camp, in which [[Tage Erlander]] ([[prime minister of Sweden]]), participated.<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" /><ref name=\"stadsmuseum-ssu\">{{cite web|title=Skarpn\u00e4ck, socialdemokratiskt ungdomsl\u00e4ger|publisher=Stockholms stadsmuseum|url=http://www.stockholmskallan.se/index.php?sokning=2&action=visaPost&plats=Skarpn%E4ck&start=20&mediaId=12238&post=24&tillbaka=7#|accessdate=2010-08-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Publications of the Social-Democratic and Socialist Internationals 1914-2000 |publisher=Socialist Internationals|url=http://library.fes.de/pdf-files/bibliothek/01035.pdf|accessdate=2010-08-03}}</ref> During the [[United Nations Conference on the Human Environment|United Nations environmental conference in 1972]], which took place in Stockholm, thousands of [[hippie]]s, [[Environmentalism|environmental activists]] and [[Left-wing politics|leftist activists]] gathered in a large tent camp at Skarpn\u00e4ck Airfield, organized mostly by the [[Hog Farm]] and other [[Woodstock]] veterans.<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" /> This also became a large musical event, with [[Progg|progressive artists]] like [[Peps Persson]], [[Kebnekajse]], [[Bl\u00e5 T\u00e5get]] and [[Tr\u00e4d, Gr\u00e4s & Stenar]] playing.<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" />\n\nWith the initiative of ''Motorf\u00f6rarnas Helnykterhetsf\u00f6rbund'', a [[Temperance movement|temperance organization]], Sweden's first [[drive-in]] [[church service]] was held at Skarpn\u00e4ck Airfield on May 30, 1957.<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" /><ref name=\"stadsmuseum\">{{cite web|title=Skarpn\u00e4cks flygf\u00e4lt|publisher=Stockholms stadsmuseum|url=http://www.stockholmskallan.se/index.php?sokning=2&action=visaPost&plats=Skarpn%E4ck&start=20&mediaId=12718&post=26&tillbaka=7#|accessdate=2010-08-03}}</ref> [[Bishop]] Odd Hagen of the [[Methodism|Methodist church]] spoke in front of 1,000 cars, and altogether around 6,000 people.<ref name=\"stadsmuseum\" /> The altar was placed on a lorry platform.<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" /><ref name=\"stadsmuseum\" />\n\nIn September 1980, the Stockholm Municipality decided that a large [[residential area]] called ''Skarpn\u00e4cksstaden'' ({{lang-en|The Skarpn\u00e4ck City}}) would be constructed on the airfield.<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" /> The baseball and greyhound-racing facilities remained and were included in the new residential area, but the greyhound-racing was closed in 2006 in favour of a [[Association football pitch|football field]] of [[artificial turf]].\n\n== Geography ==\n[[File:Skarpnack T bana perrong.jpg|thumb|Skarpn\u00e4ck metro station.]]\nSkarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet is a subdistrict of Skarpn\u00e4cks g\u00e5rd in the Skarpn\u00e4ck borough. However, since the area's construction in the 1980s, the [[Swedish police|police]] and Stockholm Municipality publish their statistics for Skarpn\u00e4cks g\u00e5rd separately between Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet and [[Pungpinan]] (the two subdistricts). Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet accounts for the majority of the Skarpn\u00e4cks g\u00e5rd district's population, and is colloquially referred to as [[Skarpn\u00e4ck borough|Skarpn\u00e4ck]]. Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet is served by a metro station named Skarpn\u00e4ck, contributing to the name confusion.\n\nSkarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet neighbours [[Flaten]] to the southeast, [[Orhem]] to the south, [[Sk\u00f6ndal]] in the [[Farsta borough]] to the southwest, [[Pungpinan]] to the northwest, [[Bagarmossen]] to the north, and the nature reserve [[Nackareservatet]] in [[Nacka Municipality]] to the east.<ref>{{cite web|title=Omr\u00e5desvis statistik, Skarpn\u00e4ck|publisher=Stockholms stads utrednings- och statistikkontor AB|url=http://www.usk.stockholm.se/internet/omrfakta/omradesvis.asp?omrade=15|accessdate=2010-08-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Omr\u00e5desvis statistik, Farsta|publisher=Stockholms stads utrednings- och statistikkontor AB|url=http://www.usk.stockholm.se/internet/omrfakta/omradesvis.asp?omrade=18|accessdate=2010-08-03}}</ref>\n\n=== Transportation ===\nThe [[Skarpn\u00e4ck metro station]] is located below ground, and has one entrance on Skarpn\u00e4cks All\u00e9. The original plan was to have two entrances, the other one located south of the current one, but those plans were never carried out.<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" /> Skarpn\u00e4ck metro station opened in 1994, making it the 100th and newest station of the [[Stockholm Metro]].<ref name=\"urbanrail\">{{cite web|title=Stockholm Metro|publisher=Urban Rail|url=http://www.urbanrail.net/eu/sto/stockhlm.htm|access-date=2010-08-03|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100720075823/http://www.urbanrail.net/eu/sto/stockhlm.htm|archive-date=2010-07-20|df=}}</ref> Skarpn\u00e4ck is the terminus of the [[Line 17 (Stockholm Metro)|green line 17]], a role it took from [[Bagarmossen metro station|Bagarmossen]] in 1994.<ref name=\"urbanrail\" /> A number of buses also pass through Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet &ndash; 180 between K\u00e4rrtorp and Orhem, 811 between [[Gullmarsplan]] and [[\u00c4lta]] and 816 between Gullmarsplan and [[Tyres\u00f6 Centrum]]. 181 to [[Farsta strand]], 172 to [[Norsborg]] and 173 to [[Sk\u00e4rholmen]] all have their terminus on Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet.<ref name=\"sl\">{{cite web|title=Ficktidtabeller, Skarpn\u00e4ck|publisher=Storstockholms Lokaltrafik|url=http://sl.se/sv/Resenar/Planera-resa/Tidtabeller/?season=0&type=0&search=Skarpn%C3%A4ck&booklet=|accessdate=2010-08-03}}</ref>\n\n== Architecture ==\n[[File:Pilotgatan_2008.jpg|thumb|Pilotgatan, Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet.]]\n[[File:Skarpnack_2008a.jpg|thumb|View of northern Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet from the Bagarmossen side.]]\n[[File:Skarpnack allee 1.jpg|thumb|Skarpn\u00e4cks All\u00e9, Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet.]]\nThe construction of ''Skarpn\u00e4cksstaden'' began in the early 1980s. This was a few years after the finish of the [[Million Programme]], a project designed to offer everyone a reasonably priced home by building one million [[dwelling]]s in a 10-year period, 1965 to 1974. While the project succeeded, it was heavily criticized for the buildings' lack of aesthetics, the common image of a Million Programme building being a large, gray apartment complex of cement in a monotone [[dormitory suburb]].\n\nThus, with the planning of ''Skarpn\u00e4cksstaden'', time was spent to assure that the mistakes of the Million Programme were not repeated. The area was to move away from the mass production-style of the Million Programme, instead focusing on a variation of houses and apartments.<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" /><ref name=\"sthlmsk\u00e4llan-pdf\">{{cite web|title=Skarpn\u00e4ck|publisher=AB Stockholmshem|url=http://www.stockholmskallan.se/php/fupload/SMF/SD/SSMB_0006396_01.pdf|date=1996|accessdate=2010-08-03}}</ref> Skarpn\u00e4cksstaden was intended to be a complete [[town|small town]] in itself, with housing, workplaces and schools.<ref name=\"sthlmsk\u00e4llan-pdf\" /> In all, the classical elements of a small town inspired the design of Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet greatly, for instance in the structure of [[City block|blocks]] with [[street]]s, [[quadrangle (architecture)|square]]s and [[courtyard]]s.<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" /><ref name=\"sthlmsk\u00e4llan-pdf\" />\n\nThe characteristical orange-red [[brick]] buildings of Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet have received international attention, partially because the relatively large area consists of exclusively such buildings.<ref name=\"hsb\">{{cite web|title=Historik|publisher=HSB|url=http://www.hsb.se/stockholm/flygledaren/om-flygledaren/1_28276?select=1.28276\n|accessdate=2010-08-03}}</ref> Other than the apartment buildings, a number of row-houses and an [[industrial region|industrial area]] were built around the same time, painted in similar colours to fit with the rest of Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet.<ref name=\"hsb\" /> The design, by [[architect]] Leif Blomquist, has received several awards for its extraordinarity.<ref name=\"hsb\" /> Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet has considerably few connections with other districts, giving it the image of a slightly isolated area, and some argue that a road to Bagarmossen with new [[housing development]]s would lead to a better [[Social integration|integration]] of Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet, while others think that the nature between the two areas should be preserved.<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" />\n\n== Housing ==\n\nBetween 1982 and 1990, 3,390 apartments were built on Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet.<ref name=\"skarpnacksfaltet-stats\" /> On December 31, 1990, 1,419 of those were publicly owned rental [[apartment]]s, 736 were privately owned rental apartments and 1,235 were [[condominium]]s. As of December 31, 2009, there are 3,564 apartments on Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet - 1,323 publicly owned rental apartments, 194 privately owned rental apartments and 2,047 condominiums. There are also 277 other dwellings, mostly [[row-house]]s.<ref name=\"skarpnacksfaltet-stats\" />\n\nAs of December 31, 2009, there are 332 [[studio apartment]]s, 1,155 two-room apartments, 1,199 three-room apartments, 816 four-room apartments and 150 five-room apartments.<ref name=\"skarpnacksfaltet-stats\" /> Most of the other 277 dwellings have four or five rooms.<ref name=\"skarpnacksfaltet-stats\" /> Given that there were many big apartments on Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet, plenty of families with children moved there, which lead to Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet having the highest child density (highest number of children per square km) in [[northern Europe]] during the mid-90s.<ref name=\"hsb\" /><ref name=\"segelflygaren\">{{cite web|title=Omgivningar och Historia|publisher=BRF Segelflygaren|url=http://www.segelflygaren.net/omgivningar.php|access-date=2010-08-03|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724060708/http://www.segelflygaren.net/omgivningar.php|archive-date=2011-07-24|df=}}</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\nSkarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet has 8,734 inhabitants as of December 31, 2009.<ref name=\"skarpnacksfaltet-stats\" /> People with a foreign background (born outside Sweden, or with both parents born outside Sweden) made up for 42.8% of Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet's population, compared to 26.6% of the entire Skarpn\u00e4ck borough, and 28.7% of Stockholm as a whole.<ref name=\"skarpnacksfaltet-stats\" /><ref name=\"skarpnack-stats\">{{cite web|title=Omr\u00e5desfakta stadsdelsomr\u00e5de Skarpn\u00e4ck|publisher=Stockholms Stads Utrednings- och Statistikkontor AB|url=http://www.usk.stockholm.se/tabellverktyg/tv.aspx?projekt=omradesfakta&omrade=sdo15|accessdate=2010-08-03}}</ref><ref name=\"stockholm-stats\">{{cite web|title=Omr\u00e5desfakta hela staden|publisher=Stockholms Stads Utrednings- och Statistikkontor AB|url=http://www.usk.stockholm.se/tabellverktyg/tv.aspx?projekt=omradesfakta&omrade=0|accessdate=2010-08-03}}</ref>\n\nThe [[unemployment rate]] of Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet was 4.8% on October 31, 2009.<ref name=\"skarpnacksfaltet-stats\" /> In comparison, 3.8% of the Skarpn\u00e4ck borough population were unemployed, and 3.6% of Stockholm as a whole.<ref name=\"skarpnack-stats\" /><ref name=\"stockholm-stats\" /> The average income on Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet was 227,000 [[Swedish kronor]], this was below the Skarpn\u00e4ck borough average of 250,200 Swedish kronor as well as the Stockholm average of 294,500 Swedish kronor.<ref name=\"skarpnacksfaltet-stats\" /><ref name=\"skarpnack-stats\" /><ref name=\"stockholm-stats\" />\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Skarpn\u00e4ck borough|Skarpn\u00e4ck]]\n*[[Skarpn\u00e4cks g\u00e5rd]]\n*[[Skarpn\u00e4ck metro station]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Skarpnacksfaltet}}\n[[Category:Geography of Stockholm]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n| name                    = Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet\n| native_name             = \n| native_name_lang        = <!-- ISO 639-2 code e.g. \"fr\" for French. If more than one, use {{lang}} instead -->\n| settlement_type         = Subdistrict of Stockholm\n| image_skyline           = Skarpnack allee 2.jpg\n| image_alt               = Skarpn\u00e4cks All\u00e9\n| image_caption           = Skarpn\u00e4cks All\u00e9\n| image_flag              = \n| flag_alt                = \n| image_seal              = \n| seal_alt                = \n| image_shield            = \n| shield_alt              = \n| nickname                = \n| motto                   = \n| image_map               = \n| map_alt                 = \n| map_caption             = \n| pushpin_map             =Sweden Stockholm Municipality\n| pushpin_label_position  = none\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_mapsize         = 250\n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location of Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet in [[Stockholm Municipality]]\n| coordinates             = {{coord|59|16|4.28|N|18|7|6.65|E|display=inline,title}}\n| coor_pinpoint           = \n| coordinates_footnotes   = \n| subdivision_type        = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = [[Sweden]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Provinces of Sweden|Province]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[S\u00f6dermanland]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[Counties of Sweden|County]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Stockholm County]]\n| subdivision_type3       = [[Municipalities of Sweden|Municipality]]\n| subdivision_name3       = [[Stockholm Municipality]]\n| subdivision_type4       = [[Boroughs of Stockholm|Borough]]\n| subdivision_name4       = [[Skarpn\u00e4ck borough]]\n| subdivision_type5       = [[District]]\n| subdivision_name5       = [[Skarpn\u00e4cks g\u00e5rd]]\n| established_title       = \n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| seat_type               = \n| seat                    = \n| government_footnotes    = \n| leader_party            = \n| leader_title            = \n| leader_name             = \n| unit_pref               = Metric<!-- or US or UK -->\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = \n| area_land_km2           = \n| area_water_km2          = \n| area_water_percent      = \n| area_note               = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_footnotes    = <ref name=\"skarpnacksfaltet-stats\">{{cite web|title=Omr\u00e5desfakta delomr\u00e5de Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet|publisher=Stockholms stads utrednings- och statistikkontor AB|url=http://www.usk.stockholm.se/tabellverktyg/tv.aspx?projekt=omradesfakta&omrade=sp10|accessdate=2010-08-03}}</ref>\n| population_total        = 8,734\n| population_as_of        = December 31, 2009\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_note         = \n| timezone1               = \n| utc_offset1             = \n| timezone1_DST           = \n| utc_offset1_DST         = \n| postal_code_type        = \n| postal_code             = \n| area_code_type          = \n| area_code               = \n| iso_code                = \n| website                 = <!-- [http://www.example.com example.com] -->\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet''' ({{lang-en|The Skarpn\u00e4ck Field}}) is a subdistrict of [[Skarpn\u00e4cks G\u00e5rd]] in the [[Skarpn\u00e4ck borough]] of [[Stockholm]], [[Sweden]]. Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet was built in the 1980s, and has 8,734 inhabitants as of December 31, 2009.<ref name=\"skarpnacksfaltet-stats\" />\n\n== History ==\n[[Archaeology|Archaeological finding]]s, such as a [[hill fort]] and [[stone circle]]s near [[Flatensj\u00f6n]], indicate that Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet and nearby areas were populated by [[viking]]s as early as the 10th century.<ref name=\"historik-care\">{{cite web|title=Fr\u00e5n vikingatid till nutid - en liten historik|publisher=Skarpn\u00e4ck Care AB|url=http://www.segelflygaren.net/historik_skarp.pdf|access-date=2010-08-03|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724060544/http://www.segelflygaren.net/historik_skarp.pdf|archive-date=2011-07-24|df=}}</ref><ref name=\"skarpnack-book\">{{cite book |last= Roxell |first= Pia |author2=Eva Wernlid  |title= Skarpn\u00e4ck - Tegelstaden p\u00e5 f\u00e4ltet |publisher= Stockholmia F\u00f6rlag |year= 2009 |isbn= 978-91-7031-219-9}}</ref>\n\n=== Skarpa by ===\n[[Skarpa]], a [[cottage]] of the [[\u00c5rsta Castle|\u00c5rsta]] property, was first mentioned in the will of [[Valdemar, Duke of Finland|Duke Valdemar]] in 1318, where it was listed as one of his donations to [[Uppsala domkyrka]].<ref name=\"hembygd-skarpaby\">{{cite web|title=Skarpa by|publisher=Bagarmossens hembygdsf\u00f6rening|url=http://www.bagarmossen.org/skpnck/Skarpaby.asp|accessdate=2010-08-03}}</ref> Skarpa derives from the word ''skarp'' ({{lang-en|sharp}}), and is believed to have indicated the soil quality, which was heavy [[loam]].<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" /><ref name=\"hembygd-skarpaby\" /> It is believed that the small village of [[Skarpa by]], with the Skarpa cottage, also consisted of three [[homestead (buildings)|homestead]]s dating as far back as the 13th century.<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" />\n\n[[File:Skarpnacks gard 2008.jpg|left|thumb|The main building of Skarpn\u00e4cks g\u00e5rd, as constructed in the 1860s.]]\nAccording to a document from 1432, Skarpa was sold by the [[Archdiocese of Uppsala]] to Hans Kr\u00f6pelin, the chieftain of [[Eric of Pomerania]], who was the [[King of Sweden]] at the time.<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" /> Like in the will of Duke Valdemar, Skarpa was part of the \u00c5rsta property.<ref name=\"historik-care\" /><ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" />\n\nDuring the 17th century, the land and cottages of Skarpa by were included in the [[Tyres\u00f6]] property. Tyres\u00f6 was owned by the [[Oxenstierna]] family, which constructed a mansion in Skarpa by. A countess of the family (Maria Sofia de la Gardie<ref name=\"historik-care\" />) made Skarpa a manor ({{lang-sv|s\u00e4teri}}) which she named ''Skarpn\u00e4ck''.<ref name=\"historik-care\" /><ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" /> The manor continued to grow in the 18th century, now housing workers and farmers. The manor switched owners a few times, and in the beginning of the 19th century, there were almost 30 buildings in Skarpn\u00e4cks g\u00e5rd.<ref name=\"historik-care\" /><ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" /> The last owner, Friedrich Neum\u00fcller, constructed the main building which still exists today, roughly 150 years later.<ref name=\"historik-care\" /> Eventually, in 1922, the property was sold to the Stockholm Municipality.<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" />\n\n=== Skarpn\u00e4ck Airfield ===\n[[File:Segelflyg 1972.jpg|left|thumb|Sailplane at Skarpn\u00e4ck in 1972.]]\nThe [[Skarpn\u00e4ck Airfield]] was constructed on Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet around 1940.<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" /> Originally intended to be a reserve airfield for the [[Swedish military|military]], those plans were soon abandoned, and in 1943, ''Stockholms Segelflygklubb'' ({{lang-en|Stockholm's Sailplane Association}}) moved its operations to the airfield.<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" /><ref name=\"ssfk\">{{cite web|title=Om klubben|publisher=Stockholms Segelflygklubb|url=http://www4.idrottonline.se/templates/Page.aspx?id=378185|accessdate=2010-08-03}}</ref> The airfield was commonly used for other activities, including balloon flying, races such as the [[1948 Stockholm Grand Prix]], baseball and [[greyhound racing]].<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" />\n\nThe airfield became a centre for [[Counterculture|alternative society movements]].<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" /> In August 1950, the [[International Union of Socialist Youth]], together with the [[Swedish Social Democratic Youth Association]], organized a week-long international tent camp, in which [[Tage Erlander]] ([[prime minister of Sweden]]), participated.<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" /><ref name=\"stadsmuseum-ssu\">{{cite web|title=Skarpn\u00e4ck, socialdemokratiskt ungdomsl\u00e4ger|publisher=Stockholms stadsmuseum|url=http://www.stockholmskallan.se/index.php?sokning=2&action=visaPost&plats=Skarpn%E4ck&start=20&mediaId=12238&post=24&tillbaka=7#|accessdate=2010-08-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Publications of the Social-Democratic and Socialist Internationals 1914-2000 |publisher=Socialist Internationals|url=http://library.fes.de/pdf-files/bibliothek/01035.pdf|accessdate=2010-08-03}}</ref> During the [[United Nations Conference on the Human Environment|United Nations environmental conference in 1972]], which took place in Stockholm, thousands of [[hippie]]s, [[Environmentalism|environmental activists]] and [[Left-wing politics|leftist activists]] gathered in a large tent camp at Skarpn\u00e4ck Airfield, organized mostly by the [[Hog Farm]] and other [[Woodstock]] veterans.<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" /> This also became a large musical event, with [[Progg|progressive artists]] like [[Peps Persson]], [[Kebnekajse]], [[Bl\u00e5 T\u00e5get]] and [[Tr\u00e4d, Gr\u00e4s & Stenar]] playing.<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" />\n\nWith the initiative of ''Motorf\u00f6rarnas Helnykterhetsf\u00f6rbund'', a [[Temperance movement|temperance organization]], Sweden's first [[drive-in]] [[church service]] was held at Skarpn\u00e4ck Airfield on May 30, 1957.<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" /><ref name=\"stadsmuseum\">{{cite web|title=Skarpn\u00e4cks flygf\u00e4lt|publisher=Stockholms stadsmuseum|url=http://www.stockholmskallan.se/index.php?sokning=2&action=visaPost&plats=Skarpn%E4ck&start=20&mediaId=12718&post=26&tillbaka=7#|accessdate=2010-08-03}}</ref> [[Bishop]] Odd Hagen of the [[Methodism|Methodist church]] spoke in front of 1,000 cars, and altogether around 6,000 people.<ref name=\"stadsmuseum\" /> The altar was placed on a lorry platform.<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" /><ref name=\"stadsmuseum\" />\n\nIn September 1980, the Stockholm Municipality decided that a large [[residential area]] called ''Skarpn\u00e4cksstaden'' ({{lang-en|The Skarpn\u00e4ck City}}) would be constructed on the airfield.<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" /> The baseball and greyhound-racing facilities remained and were included in the new residential area, but the greyhound-racing was closed in 2006 in favour of a [[Association football pitch|football field]] of [[artificial turf]].\n\n== Geography ==\n[[File:Skarpnack T bana perrong.jpg|thumb|Skarpn\u00e4ck metro station.]]\nSkarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet is a subdistrict of Skarpn\u00e4cks g\u00e5rd in the Skarpn\u00e4ck borough. However, since the area's construction in the 1980s, the [[Swedish police|police]] and Stockholm Municipality publish their statistics for Skarpn\u00e4cks g\u00e5rd separately between Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet and [[Pungpinan]] (the two subdistricts). Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet accounts for the majority of the Skarpn\u00e4cks g\u00e5rd district's population, and is colloquially referred to as [[Skarpn\u00e4ck borough|Skarpn\u00e4ck]]. Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet is served by a metro station named Skarpn\u00e4ck, contributing to the name confusion.\n\nSkarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet neighbours [[Flaten]] to the southeast, [[Orhem]] to the south, [[Sk\u00f6ndal]] in the [[Farsta borough]] to the southwest, [[Pungpinan]] to the northwest, [[Bagarmossen]] to the north, and the nature reserve [[Nackareservatet]] in [[Nacka Municipality]] to the east.<ref>{{cite web|title=Omr\u00e5desvis statistik, Skarpn\u00e4ck|publisher=Stockholms stads utrednings- och statistikkontor AB|url=http://www.usk.stockholm.se/internet/omrfakta/omradesvis.asp?omrade=15|accessdate=2010-08-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Omr\u00e5desvis statistik, Farsta|publisher=Stockholms stads utrednings- och statistikkontor AB|url=http://www.usk.stockholm.se/internet/omrfakta/omradesvis.asp?omrade=18|accessdate=2010-08-03}}</ref>\n\n=== Transportation ===\nThe [[Skarpn\u00e4ck metro station]] is located below ground, and has one entrance on Skarpn\u00e4cks All\u00e9. The original plan was to have two entrances, the other one located south of the current one, but those plans were never carried out.<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" /> Skarpn\u00e4ck metro station opened in 1994, making it the 100th and newest station of the [[Stockholm Metro]].<ref name=\"urbanrail\">{{cite web|title=Stockholm Metro|publisher=Urban Rail|url=http://www.urbanrail.net/eu/sto/stockhlm.htm|access-date=2010-08-03|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100720075823/http://www.urbanrail.net/eu/sto/stockhlm.htm|archive-date=2010-07-20|df=}}</ref> Skarpn\u00e4ck is the terminus of the [[Line 17 (Stockholm Metro)|green line 17]], a role it took from [[Bagarmossen metro station|Bagarmossen]] in 1994.<ref name=\"urbanrail\" /> A number of buses also pass through Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet &ndash; 180 between K\u00e4rrtorp and Orhem, 811 between [[Gullmarsplan]] and [[\u00c4lta]] and 816 between Gullmarsplan and [[Tyres\u00f6 Centrum]]. 181 to [[Farsta strand]], 172 to [[Norsborg]] and 173 to [[Sk\u00e4rholmen]] all have their terminus on Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet.<ref name=\"sl\">{{cite web|title=Ficktidtabeller, Skarpn\u00e4ck|publisher=Storstockholms Lokaltrafik|url=http://sl.se/sv/Resenar/Planera-resa/Tidtabeller/?season=0&type=0&search=Skarpn%C3%A4ck&booklet=|accessdate=2010-08-03}}</ref>\n\n== Architecture ==\n[[File:Pilotgatan_2008.jpg|thumb|Pilotgatan, Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet.]]\n[[File:Skarpnack_2008a.jpg|thumb|View of northern Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet from the Bagarmossen side.]]\n[[File:Skarpnack allee 1.jpg|thumb|Skarpn\u00e4cks All\u00e9, Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet.]]\nThe construction of ''Skarpn\u00e4cksstaden'' began in the early 1980s. This was a few years after the finish of the [[Million Programme]], a project designed to offer everyone a reasonably priced home by building one million [[dwelling]]s in a 10-year period, 1965 to 1974. While the project succeeded, it was heavily criticized for the buildings' lack of aesthetics, the common image of a Million Programme building being a large, gray apartment complex of cement in a monotone [[dormitory suburb]].\n\nThus, with the planning of ''Skarpn\u00e4cksstaden'', time was spent to assure that the mistakes of the Million Programme were not repeated. The area was to move away from the mass production-style of the Million Programme, instead focusing on a variation of houses and apartments.<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" /><ref name=\"sthlmsk\u00e4llan-pdf\">{{cite web|title=Skarpn\u00e4ck|publisher=AB Stockholmshem|url=http://www.stockholmskallan.se/php/fupload/SMF/SD/SSMB_0006396_01.pdf|date=1996|accessdate=2010-08-03}}</ref> Skarpn\u00e4cksstaden was intended to be a complete [[town|small town]] in itself, with housing, workplaces and schools.<ref name=\"sthlmsk\u00e4llan-pdf\" /> In all, the classical elements of a small town inspired the design of Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet greatly, for instance in the structure of [[City block|blocks]] with [[street]]s, [[quadrangle (architecture)|square]]s and [[courtyard]]s.<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" /><ref name=\"sthlmsk\u00e4llan-pdf\" />\n\nThe characteristical orange-red [[brick]] buildings of Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet have received international attention, partially because the relatively large area consists of exclusively such buildings.<ref name=\"hsb\">{{cite web|title=Historik|publisher=HSB|url=http://www.hsb.se/stockholm/flygledaren/om-flygledaren/1_28276?select=1.28276\n|accessdate=2010-08-03}}</ref> Other than the apartment buildings, a number of row-houses and an [[industrial region|industrial area]] were built around the same time, painted in similar colours to fit with the rest of Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet.<ref name=\"hsb\" /> The design, by [[architect]] Leif Blomquist, has received several awards for its extraordinarity.<ref name=\"hsb\" /> Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet has considerably few connections with other districts, giving it the image of a slightly isolated area, and some argue that a road to Bagarmossen with new [[housing development]]s would lead to a better [[Social integration|integration]] of Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet, while others think that the nature between the two areas should be preserved.<ref name=\"skarpnack-book\" />\n\n== Housing ==\n\nBetween 1982 and 1990, 3,390 apartments were built on Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet.<ref name=\"skarpnacksfaltet-stats\" /> On December 31, 1990, 1,419 of those were publicly owned rental [[apartment]]s, 736 were privately owned rental apartments and 1,235 were [[condominium]]s. As of December 31, 2009, there are 3,564 apartments on Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet - 1,323 publicly owned rental apartments, 194 privately owned rental apartments and 2,047 condominiums. There are also 277 other dwellings, mostly [[row-house]]s.<ref name=\"skarpnacksfaltet-stats\" />\n\nAs of December 31, 2009, there are 332 [[studio apartment]]s, 1,155 two-room apartments, 1,199 three-room apartments, 816 four-room apartments and 150 five-room apartments.<ref name=\"skarpnacksfaltet-stats\" /> Most of the other 277 dwellings have four or five rooms.<ref name=\"skarpnacksfaltet-stats\" /> Given that there were many big apartments on Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet, plenty of families with children moved there, which lead to Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet having the highest child density (highest number of children per square km) in [[northern Europe]] during the mid-90s.<ref name=\"hsb\" /><ref name=\"segelflygaren\">{{cite web|title=Omgivningar och Historia|publisher=BRF Segelflygaren|url=http://www.segelflygaren.net/omgivningar.php|access-date=2010-08-03|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724060708/http://www.segelflygaren.net/omgivningar.php|archive-date=2011-07-24|df=}}</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\nSkarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet has 8,734 inhabitants as of December 31, 2009.<ref name=\"skarpnacksfaltet-stats\" /> People with a foreign background (born outside Sweden, or with both parents born outside Sweden) made up for 42.8% of Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet's population, compared to 26.6% of the entire Skarpn\u00e4ck borough, and 28.7% of Stockholm as a whole.<ref name=\"skarpnacksfaltet-stats\" /><ref name=\"skarpnack-stats\">{{cite web|title=Omr\u00e5desfakta stadsdelsomr\u00e5de Skarpn\u00e4ck|publisher=Stockholms Stads Utrednings- och Statistikkontor AB|url=http://www.usk.stockholm.se/tabellverktyg/tv.aspx?projekt=omradesfakta&omrade=sdo15|accessdate=2010-08-03}}</ref><ref name=\"stockholm-stats\">{{cite web|title=Omr\u00e5desfakta hela staden|publisher=Stockholms Stads Utrednings- och Statistikkontor AB|url=http://www.usk.stockholm.se/tabellverktyg/tv.aspx?projekt=omradesfakta&omrade=0|accessdate=2010-08-03}}</ref>\n\nThe [[unemployment rate]] of Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet was 4.8% on October 31, 2009.<ref name=\"skarpnacksfaltet-stats\" /> In comparison, 3.8% of the Skarpn\u00e4ck borough population were unemployed, and 3.6% of Stockholm as a whole.<ref name=\"skarpnack-stats\" /><ref name=\"stockholm-stats\" /> The average income on Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet was 227,000 [[Swedish kronor]], this was below the Skarpn\u00e4ck borough average of 250,200 Swedish kronor as well as the Stockholm average of 294,500 Swedish kronor.<ref name=\"skarpnacksfaltet-stats\" /><ref name=\"skarpnack-stats\" /><ref name=\"stockholm-stats\" />\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Skarpn\u00e4ck borough|Skarpn\u00e4ck]]\n*[[Skarpn\u00e4cks g\u00e5rd]]\n*[[Skarpn\u00e4ck metro station]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Skarpnacksfaltet}}\n[[Category:Geography of Stockholm]]\n", "name_user": "Billinghurst", "label": "safe", "comment": "(GR)File renamed:File:Segelflyg 1972.jpg\u2192File:Segelflyg Skarpn\u00e4cksf\u00e4ltet maj 1972.jpgCriterion 1(original uploader\u2019s request) \u00b7 mistake", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skarpn%C3%A4cksf%C3%A4ltet"}
{"title_page": "Tony Loughlan", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Tony Loughlan\n| image = \n| fullname = Antony John Loughlan\n| height =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1970|1|19|df=y}}\n| birth_place = Croydon, England\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 =   1986\u20131988\n| youthclubs1 =   [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]]\n|  years1 =   1988\u20131989\n| years2 =  1989\u20131993\n| years3 =  1993\u20131994\n| years4 =  1993\u20131994\n| years5 =  1994\u20131995\n| years6 =  1995\u20131996\n| years7 =  1996\u20131998\n|  clubs1 =  [[Leicester United F.C.|Leicester United]]\n| clubs2 =  [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]]\n| clubs3 =  [[Kettering Town F.C.|Kettering Town]]\n| clubs4 =  [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]]\n| clubs5 =  [[Dundalk F.C.|Dundalk]]\n| clubs6 =  [[Hinckley Town F.C.|Hinckley Town]]\n| clubs7 =  [[Corby Town F.C.|Corby Town]]\n| caps1 =\n| caps2 =   2\n| caps3 =   5\n| caps4 =  12\n| caps5 =  11\n| goals1 =\n| goals2 =  1\n| goals3 =  1\n| goals4 =  2\n| goals5 =  0\n}}\n'''Tony Loughlan''' (born 19 January 1970) is a Scottish retired footballer. Having held senior coaching positions at [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]], [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] and [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] under [[Roy Keane]].\n\n==Playing career==\nLoughlan began his career in the youth team at [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] but failed to turn professional and, instead, dropped into non-league football with [[Leicester United F.C.|Leicester United]].\n\nIn August 1989, Loughlan and teammate [[Neil Lyne]] were signed by [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]]; the transfer would later be highlighted in the 1997 [[Premier League]] report of [[Rick Parry]], Robert Reid QC and [[Steve Coppell]] on bung culture in football.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/htmlContent.jhtml?html=/archive/1997/09/20/sfnwin20.html |title=Bung-busters prepare to act on 'cult of dishonesty' |publisher=Daily Telegraph |author=Henry Winter |date=20 September 1997 |accessdate=1 April 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041125140520/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/htmlContent.jhtml?html=%2Farchive%2F1997%2F09%2F20%2Fsfnwin20.html |archivedate=25 November 2004 }}</ref> [[Brian Clough]] and [[Ron Fenton]] would later be charged with misconduct by the FA over the affair though the charges against Clough were later dropped.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_19980123/ai_n9650951/pg_2\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070513201317/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_19980123/ai_n9650951/pg_2\n|url-status=dead\n|archive-date=13 May 2007\n|title=Forest plan vigorous defence to FA 'bungs' charges\n|publisher=The Independent\n|author=Jon Culley\n|date=23 January 1998\n|accessdate=1 April 2008}}</ref> Loughlan made his debut for Forest against [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]] on 30 March 1991; he scored after just 36 seconds. He would make one further league appearance before injury blighted his progress and he was released at the end of the 1992\u20131993 season.\n\nIn the summer of 1993 he joined [[Kettering Town F.C.|Kettering Town]], a club his father John had played for in the 1970s. In October 1993, he returned to the [[Football League]] with [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]], marking his debut on 30 October 1993 with the only goal as Lincoln defeated [[Rochdale A.F.C|Rochdale]] at [[Spotland]] for the first time in 26 years.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.redimps.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10440~1416755,00.html \n |title=We've Met (Rochdale) Before \n |publisher=Lincoln City F.C. Official Website \n |date=16 January 2009 \n |accessdate=23 April 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091212041140/http://www.redimps.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10440~1416755%2C00.html \n |archivedate=12 December 2009 \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref> Once again, he struggled with injury and left Lincoln at the end of the season.\n\nHe linked up with [[Dundalk F.C.|Dundalk]] for the 1994\u201395 season, picking up a [[League of Ireland]] winner's medal as [[Dermot Keely]]'s side captured the title on the final day of the season with a 2\u20130 win over [[Galway United F.C.|Galway United]]. He returned to England, joining [[Hinckley Town F.C.|Hinckley Town]] at the beginning of the 1995\u201396 season. After another spell on the sidelines due to injury, he joined [[Corby Town F.C.|Corby Town]] in December 1996 where he remained for over a season before injuries forced him into retirement.\n\n==Coaching career==\nIn 2001, he began coaching on a part-time basis at [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]]'s academy, moving into a full-time role in the summer of 2003 with responsibility for the eight to 13-year-old groups.<ref>{{cite news\n |url=http://www.lcfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/LatestNews/0,,10274~412830,00.html\n |title=Academy latest \n |publisher=Leicester City Football Club \n |date=18 August 2003 \n |accessdate=1 April 2008 \n}}{{dead link|date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In August 2006 he left his role as Academy Coach at Leicester<ref>{{cite news\n |url=http://www.lcfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/LatestNews/0,,10274~889130,00.html\n |title=Loughlan joins Black Cats \n |publisher=Leicester City Football Club \n |date=29 August 2006 \n |accessdate=1 April 2008 \n}}{{dead link|date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> to become Head Coach at [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] under the management of his former Forest teammate and long-term friend [[Roy Keane]], with Keane being quoted as saying \"he is someone I trust and I have great faith in him. He's the one person I've kept in touch with over 20 years.\"<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_20060830/ai_n16693343\n|title=Tony who? The loyal friend thrown into the limelight\n|publisher=The Independent\n|author=Sam Wallace\n|date=30 August 2006\n|accessdate=1 April 2008}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> Following the departure of Keane as manager on 4 December 2008,<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/sunderland/7764671.stm\n|title=Keane resigns as Sunderland boss\n|date=4 December 2008\n|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]\n|accessdate=24 April 2009}}</ref> Loughlan was placed on [[gardening leave]] whilst a severance package could be agreed.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/jan/23/ricky-sbragia-sunderland\n|title=Sbragia wants a director of football at Sunderland\n|publisher=[[The Guardian]]\n|author=Louise Taylor\n|date=24 January 2009\n|accessdate=24 April 2009}}</ref> In January 2009, media speculation linked him with a coaching role with [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] under their newly appointed manager [[Simon Grayson]] after reports emerged that Grayson had agreed a deal in principle with a coach that is currently on [[gardening leave]] from a [[Premier League]] club.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/leedsunited/Leeds-United-Snodin-move-in.4868419.jp\n|title=Leeds United: Snodin move in balance as Little rejects Leeds\n|publisher=[[Yorkshire Evening Post]]\n|date=13 January 2009\n|author=Leon Wobschall\n|accessdate=24 April 2009}}</ref> However, the coach in question was not Loughlan but [[Glynn Snodin]] who had been on similar leave from [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] following the departure of [[Alan Curbishley]] and who was appointed to Grayson's staff on 2 February 2009.<ref>{{cite web\n |url        = http://www.leedsunited.com/page/LatestNewsDetail/0,,10273~1541837,00.html\n |archive-url = https://archive.is/20120805101935/http://www.leedsunited.com/page/LatestNewsDetail/0,,10273~1541837,00.html\n |url-status   = dead\n |archive-date = 5 August 2012\n |title      = Glynn Snodin returns\n |publisher  = Leeds United A.F.C. Official Website\n |date       = 2 February 2009\n |accessdate = 24 April 2009\n}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 April 2009, the same day that [[Roy Keane]] was appointed manager, he joined [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] as assistant manager on a two-year contract.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.itfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10272~1637007,00.html \n |title=Tony joins Town \n |publisher=Ipswich Town F.C. Official Website \n |date=23 April 2009 \n |accessdate=23 April 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090424205936/http://www.itfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10272~1637007%2C00.html \n |archivedate=24 April 2009 \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 June 2011 he joined [[Football League Championship|Championship]] side [[Watford F.C.|Watford]], under new manager [[Sean Dyche]], a former teammate at Nottingham Forest. After Dyche's departure from Watford, Loughlan also left with immediate effect. He later rejoined Dyche at his new club [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]].\n<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.watfordfc.com/page/NewsDetail/0,,10400~2384411,00.html \n |title=NEWS: COACHING DUO APPOINTED \n |publisher=Watford F.C. Official Website \n |date=30 June 2011 \n |accessdate=1 July 2011 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110703062037/http://www.watfordfc.com/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10400~2384411%2C00.html \n |archivedate=3 July 2011 \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Honours==\n*'''League of Ireland'''\n** Dundalk \u2013 1994\u201395\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110929074008/http://www.redimps.com/archive3/index.mv?cat=players&drop=playerdetsdrop&play=loug01 Lincoln City F.C. Official Archive Profile]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Loughlan, Tony}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Leicester United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Nottingham Forest F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Kettering Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Lincoln City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Dundalk F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Hinckley Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Corby Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:League of Ireland players]]\n[[Category:Sunderland A.F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Watford F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Burnley F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Tony Loughlan\n| image = \n| fullname = Antony John Loughlan\n| height =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1970|1|19|df=y}}\n| birth_place = Croydon\n|\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 =   1986\u20131988\n| youthclubs1 =   [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]]\n|  years1 =   1988\u20131989\n| years2 =  1989\u20131993\n| years3 =  1993\u20131994\n| years4 =  1993\u20131994\n| years5 =  1994\u20131995\n| years6 =  1995\u20131996\n| years7 =  1996\u20131998\n|  clubs1 =  [[Leicester United F.C.|Leicester United]]\n| clubs2 =  [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]]\n| clubs3 =  [[Kettering Town F.C.|Kettering Town]]\n| clubs4 =  [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]]\n| clubs5 =  [[Dundalk F.C.|Dundalk]]\n| clubs6 =  [[Hinckley Town F.C.|Hinckley Town]]\n| clubs7 =  [[Corby Town F.C.|Corby Town]]\n| caps1 =\n| caps2 =   2\n| caps3 =   5\n| caps4 =  12\n| caps5 =  11\n| goals1 =\n| goals2 =  1\n| goals3 =  1\n| goals4 =  2\n| goals5 =  0\n}}\n'''Tony Loughlan''' (born 19 January 1970) is a Scottish retired footballer. Having held senior coaching positions at [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]], [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] and [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] under [[Roy Keane]].\n\n==Playing career==\nLoughlan began his career in the youth team at [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] but failed to turn professional and, instead, dropped into non-league football with [[Leicester United F.C.|Leicester United]].\n\nIn August 1989, Loughlan and teammate [[Neil Lyne]] were signed by [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]]; the transfer would later be highlighted in the 1997 [[Premier League]] report of [[Rick Parry]], Robert Reid QC and [[Steve Coppell]] on bung culture in football.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/htmlContent.jhtml?html=/archive/1997/09/20/sfnwin20.html |title=Bung-busters prepare to act on 'cult of dishonesty' |publisher=Daily Telegraph |author=Henry Winter |date=20 September 1997 |accessdate=1 April 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041125140520/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/htmlContent.jhtml?html=%2Farchive%2F1997%2F09%2F20%2Fsfnwin20.html |archivedate=25 November 2004 }}</ref> [[Brian Clough]] and [[Ron Fenton]] would later be charged with misconduct by the FA over the affair though the charges against Clough were later dropped.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_19980123/ai_n9650951/pg_2\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070513201317/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_19980123/ai_n9650951/pg_2\n|url-status=dead\n|archive-date=13 May 2007\n|title=Forest plan vigorous defence to FA 'bungs' charges\n|publisher=The Independent\n|author=Jon Culley\n|date=23 January 1998\n|accessdate=1 April 2008}}</ref> Loughlan made his debut for Forest against [[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]] on 30 March 1991; he scored after just 36 seconds. He would make one further league appearance before injury blighted his progress and he was released at the end of the 1992\u20131993 season.\n\nIn the summer of 1993 he joined [[Kettering Town F.C.|Kettering Town]], a club his father John had played for in the 1970s. In October 1993, he returned to the [[Football League]] with [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]], marking his debut on 30 October 1993 with the only goal as Lincoln defeated [[Rochdale A.F.C|Rochdale]] at [[Spotland]] for the first time in 26 years.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.redimps.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10440~1416755,00.html \n |title=We've Met (Rochdale) Before \n |publisher=Lincoln City F.C. Official Website \n |date=16 January 2009 \n |accessdate=23 April 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091212041140/http://www.redimps.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10440~1416755%2C00.html \n |archivedate=12 December 2009 \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref> Once again, he struggled with injury and left Lincoln at the end of the season.\n\nHe linked up with [[Dundalk F.C.|Dundalk]] for the 1994\u201395 season, picking up a [[League of Ireland]] winner's medal as [[Dermot Keely]]'s side captured the title on the final day of the season with a 2\u20130 win over [[Galway United F.C.|Galway United]]. He returned to England, joining [[Hinckley Town F.C.|Hinckley Town]] at the beginning of the 1995\u201396 season. After another spell on the sidelines due to injury, he joined [[Corby Town F.C.|Corby Town]] in December 1996 where he remained for over a season before injuries forced him into retirement.\n\n==Coaching career==\nIn 2001, he began coaching on a part-time basis at [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]]'s academy, moving into a full-time role in the summer of 2003 with responsibility for the eight to 13-year-old groups.<ref>{{cite news\n |url=http://www.lcfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/LatestNews/0,,10274~412830,00.html\n |title=Academy latest \n |publisher=Leicester City Football Club \n |date=18 August 2003 \n |accessdate=1 April 2008 \n}}{{dead link|date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In August 2006 he left his role as Academy Coach at Leicester<ref>{{cite news\n |url=http://www.lcfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/LatestNews/0,,10274~889130,00.html\n |title=Loughlan joins Black Cats \n |publisher=Leicester City Football Club \n |date=29 August 2006 \n |accessdate=1 April 2008 \n}}{{dead link|date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> to become Head Coach at [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] under the management of his former Forest teammate and long term friend [[Roy Keane]], with Keane being quoted as saying \"he is someone I trust and I have great faith in him. He's the one person I've kept in touch with over 20 years.\"<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_20060830/ai_n16693343\n|title=Tony who? The loyal friend thrown into the limelight\n|publisher=The Independent\n|author=Sam Wallace\n|date=30 August 2006\n|accessdate=1 April 2008}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> Following the departure of Keane as manager on 4 December 2008,<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/sunderland/7764671.stm\n|title=Keane resigns as Sunderland boss\n|date=4 December 2008\n|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]\n|accessdate=24 April 2009}}</ref> Loughlan was placed on [[gardening leave]] whilst a severance package could be agreed.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/jan/23/ricky-sbragia-sunderland\n|title=Sbragia wants a director of football at Sunderland\n|publisher=[[The Guardian]]\n|author=Louise Taylor\n|date=24 January 2009\n|accessdate=24 April 2009}}</ref> In January 2009, media speculation linked him with a coaching role with [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] under their newly appointed manager [[Simon Grayson]] after reports emerged that Grayson had agreed a deal in principle with a coach that is currently on [[gardening leave]] from a [[Premier League]] club.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/leedsunited/Leeds-United-Snodin-move-in.4868419.jp\n|title=Leeds United: Snodin move in balance as Little rejects Leeds\n|publisher=[[Yorkshire Evening Post]]\n|date=13 January 2009\n|author=Leon Wobschall\n|accessdate=24 April 2009}}</ref> However, the coach in question was not Loughlan but [[Glynn Snodin]] who had been on similar leave from [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] following the departure of [[Alan Curbishley]] and who was appointed to Grayson's staff on 2 February 2009.<ref>{{cite web\n |url        = http://www.leedsunited.com/page/LatestNewsDetail/0,,10273~1541837,00.html\n |archive-url = https://archive.is/20120805101935/http://www.leedsunited.com/page/LatestNewsDetail/0,,10273~1541837,00.html\n |url-status   = dead\n |archive-date = 5 August 2012\n |title      = Glynn Snodin returns\n |publisher  = Leeds United A.F.C. Official Website\n |date       = 2 February 2009\n |accessdate = 24 April 2009\n}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 April 2009, the same day that [[Roy Keane]] was appointed manager, he joined [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] as assistant manager on a two-year contract.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.itfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10272~1637007,00.html \n |title=Tony joins Town \n |publisher=Ipswich Town F.C. Official Website \n |date=23 April 2009 \n |accessdate=23 April 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090424205936/http://www.itfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10272~1637007%2C00.html \n |archivedate=24 April 2009 \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 June 2011 he joined [[Football League Championship|Championship]] side [[Watford F.C.|Watford]], under new manager [[Sean Dyche]], a former teammate at Nottingham Forest. After Dyche's departure from Watford, Loughlan also left with immediate effect. He later rejoined Dyche at his new club [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]].\n<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.watfordfc.com/page/NewsDetail/0,,10400~2384411,00.html \n |title=NEWS: COACHING DUO APPOINTED \n |publisher=Watford F.C. Official Website \n |date=30 June 2011 \n |accessdate=1 July 2011 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110703062037/http://www.watfordfc.com/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10400~2384411%2C00.html \n |archivedate=3 July 2011 \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Honours==\n*'''League of Ireland'''\n** Dundalk \u2013 1994\u201395\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110929074008/http://www.redimps.com/archive3/index.mv?cat=players&drop=playerdetsdrop&play=loug01 Lincoln City F.C. Official Archive Profile]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Loughlan, Tony}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Leicester United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Nottingham Forest F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Kettering Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Lincoln City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Dundalk F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Hinckley Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Corby Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:League of Ireland players]]\n[[Category:Sunderland A.F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Watford F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Burnley F.C. non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: long term \u2192 long-term", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tony_Loughlan"}
{"title_page": "Judgment Day (2000)", "text_new": "{{short description|2000 World Wrestling Federation pay-per-view event}}\n{{Infobox Wrestling event\n|name       = Judgment Day (2000)\n|image      = 2000JudgmentDay.jpg\n|caption    = Promotional poster featuring [[Kane (wrestler)|Kane]] \n|promotion  = [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]]\n|date       = May 21, 2000\n|venue      = [[Freedom Hall]]\n|city       = [[Louisville, Kentucky]]\n|attendance = 16,827\n|buyrate    = 420,000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wrestlingdata.com/index.php?befehl=shows&show=8350|title=WWF Judgment Day 2000|work=Wrestlingdata|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|lastevent  = [[Insurrextion (2000)|Insurrextion]]\n|nextevent  = [[King of the Ring (2000)|King of the Ring]]\n|event      = [[WWE Judgment Day|Judgment Day]]\n|lastevent2 = [[Judgment Day: In Your House|In Your House]]\n|nextevent2 = [[Judgment Day (2001)|2001]]\n}}\n'''Judgment Day (2000)''' was the first annual [[WWE Judgment Day|Judgment Day]] [[professional wrestling]] [[pay-per-view]] (PPV) [[List of WWE pay-per-view events|event]] produced by the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF). It took place on May 21, 2000, at [[Freedom Hall]] in [[Louisville, Kentucky]]. The previous [[Judgment Day: In Your House|Judgment Day]] edition was an [[In Your House]] event held in October 1998. As a result of [[Owen Hart]]'s death at [[Over the Edge (1999)|Over the Edge]] in May 1999, Judgment Day was brought back in 2000 and was rebranded as an annual WWF pay-per-view event.\n\nThe [[Card (sports)#Main event|main event]] was an [[Iron Man match]] for the [[WWE Championship|WWF Championship]] and featured [[Triple H]] facing [[Dwayne Johnson|The Rock]] with WWF Commissioner [[Shawn Michaels]] as the [[Professional wrestling match types#Special referee|special guest referee]]. Triple H defeated The Rock to win the championship by 6 [[Pin (professional wrestling)|falls]] to 5, after a [[Professional wrestling#Disqualification|disqualification]] in the final seconds by Shawn Michaels as a result of interference by the returning [[The Undertaker|Undertaker]]. Featured matches on the [[Card (sports)#Undercard|undercard]] included a [[Professional wrestling match types#Tables match|double tables match]] featuring [[D-Generation X]] ([[Brian Gerald James|Road Dogg]] and [[Sean Waltman|X-Pac]]) defeating [[Dudley Boyz|The Dudley Boyz]] ([[Mark LoMonaco|Bubba Ray Dudley]] and [[Devon Hughes|D-Von Dudley]]). The other featured match on the undercard was a [[Professional wrestling match types|Submission match]] for the [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|WWF Intercontinental Championship]] between [[Chris Benoit]] and [[Chris Jericho]], which Benoit won to retain the championship.\n\n==Storylines==\nThe main event of the evening was a 60-minute Iron man match between former World Wrestling Federation Champion Triple H and the current title holder at the time, The Rock. At WrestleMania, Vince McMahon turned on The Rock and helped Triple H retain his title, joining his daughter Stephanie and son Shane in the [[McMahon-Helmsley Faction]] with Triple H and [[D-Generation X]]. In the weeks leading up to Backlash The Rock and Triple H's hostility had reached its climax it seemed. At Backlash, with the help of Stone Cold Steve Austin, The Rock defeated Triple H. The next night on Raw Triple H stated that he wanted to take The Rock on in a 60-minute Iron man match for the World Wrestling Federation title, Shawn Michaels also got involved, requesting to be special guest referee.\n\nIn the meantime, Shane McMahon began a rivalry with the Big Show. Leading into WrestleMania Shane had actually aligned himself with Big Show, who at the time was feuding with The Rock over the finish to January's Royal Rumble. Shane interfered in their match at [[No Way Out (2000)|No Way Out]] in February and helped Big Show win, which earned Show the #1 contendership and a match with Triple H, who had won back the WWF Championship Big Show had taken from him at [[Survivor Series (1999)|Survivor Series]] in November 1999, at WrestleMania. The match eventually grew to include The Rock and Mick Foley, and Big Show was the first wrestler eliminated from the ensuing elimination fatal-four-way main event. After WrestleMania, with Shane now siding with the defending champion, Big Show began a brief period where he would imitate other wrestlers in a comedic role. This earned him ridicule from Shane, so the two began a rivalry that led to a match at Judgment Day.\n\nAnother feud involving the Faction was DX's feud with the [[Dudley Boyz]], which had started when they had defeated the [[New Age Outlaws]] at No Way Out for the [[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|WWF Tag Team Championship]] and caused the breakup of the Outlaws. Although the Dudleys did help out the Faction at times, they eventually turned on them and became heroes in the eyes of the fans. At the time Bubba Ray Dudley had taken to powerbombing many of the WWF's female wrestlers through tables and was keen on doing so to Tori, who was [[Sean Waltman|X-Pac]]'s storyline girlfriend. This led to a tables match being set for Judgment Day.\n\nThe ongoing rivalry between [[Chris Benoit]] and [[Chris Jericho]] over the [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|WWF Intercontinental Championship]] began at [[WrestleMania 2000|WresleMania 2000]] where Benoit and Jericho along with [[Kurt Angle]] faced each other in a two fall triple threat match for both Angle's Intercontinental Championship and [[WWE European Championship|European Championship]]. Benoit won the Intercontinental Championship after pinning Jericho while Jericho won the European Championship after pinning Benoit. Jericho lost the European Championship to [[Eddie Guerrero]] the following night on Raw is War after [[Chyna]] turned on Jericho for Guerrero. Benoit defended the Intercontinental Championship against Jericho at [[Backlash (2000)|Backlash]] where Benoit won by disqualification after Jericho used the title belt to defend himself from Benoit's Diving headbutt and was disqualified as a result. Benoit and Jericho had a rematch for the title on the May 4 episode of Smackdown! where Jericho won after hitting Benoit with the title belt then hitting him with the Lionsault while referee [[Earl Hebner]] was thrown out of the ring by Benoit. After aiding The Rock, confronting and insulting the McMahon-Helmsley Faction, Jericho was forced to defend the Intercontinental Championship on the May 8 episode of Raw is War. After retaining the title against Kurt Angle and Big Show, Jericho lost the Intercontinental Championship back to Benoit after special guest referee Triple H purposely got distracted by his wife [[Stephanie McMahon|Stephanie McMahon-Helmsley]] while Benoit tapped out to the Walls of Jericho and after Jericho hit him to get his attention Triple H hit Jericho from behind causing Jericho to be locked in Benoit's Crippler Crossface before Triple H called for the bell and awarded the title to Benoit despite Jericho [[Montreal Screwjob|not submitting]]. Benoit later announced that he would give Jericho a rematch for the Intercontinental Championship at Judgment Day in a [[submission match]].\n\n==Event==\n{| class=wikitable style=\"font-size:90%; margin: 0.5em 0 0.5em 1em; float: right; clear: right;\"\n|+ '''Other on-screen personnel'''\n!|Role:\n!|Name:\n|-\n|rowspan=2|English [[Sports commentators|commentators]]\n|[[Jerry Lawler]]\n|-\n|[[Jim Ross]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2|Spanish commentators\n|[[Carlos Cabrera]]\n|-\n|[[Hugo Savinovich]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[Interviewer]]s\n|[[Michael Cole (wrestling)|Michael Cole]]\n|-\n|[[Jonathan Coachman]]\n|-\n|[[Ring announcer]]\n|[[Howard Finkel]]\n|-\n|rowspan=7|[[Referee (professional wrestling)|Referees]]\n|[[Mike Chioda]]\n|-\n|[[Earl Hebner]]\n|-\n|[[Jim Korderas]]\n|-\n|[[Tim White (referee)|Tim White]]\n|-\n|[[Theodore Long]]\n|-\n|Chad Patton\n|-\n|[[Jack Doan]]\n|}\n\n===Preliminary matches===\nThe event opened with [[Team ECK]] ([[Kurt Angle]], [[Edge (wrestler)|Edge]], and [[Christian (wrestler)|Christian]]) facing [[Too Cool]] ([[Scotty 2 Hotty]], [[Brian Christopher|Grand Master Sexay]], and [[Rikishi (wrestler)|Rikishi]]). Grand Master Sexay performed the Hip Hop Drop on Edge to win the match.\n\nNext, [[Eddie Guerrero]] defended the [[WWE European Championship|WWF European Championship]] against [[Perry Saturn]] and [[Dean Malenko]] in a Triple Threat match. After [[Chyna]] hit Saturn with a bouquet of roses, Guererro pinned Malenko with an Oklahoma Roll to retain the title.\n\nAfter that, [[Shane McMahon]] faced [[Big Show]] in a Falls Count Anywhere match. After interference from [[Big Boss Man (wrestler)|Big Boss Man]], [[Test (wrestler)|Test]], [[Matt Bloom|Albert]], [[Trish Stratus]] and [[Bull Buchanan]], Shane hit Big Show with a cinderblock to win the match.\n\nLater, [[Chris Benoit]] defended the [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|WWF Intercontinental Championship]] against [[Chris Jericho]] in a Submission match. Jericho passed out to the Crippler Crossface by Benoit, meaning Benoit won the match and retained the title.\n\nIn the fifth match, [[D-Generation X]] ([[Road Dogg]] and [[Sean Waltman|X-Pac]]) faced [[The Dudley Boyz]] ([[Mark LoMonaco|Bubba Ray Dudley]] and [[Devon Hughes|D-Von Dudley]]) in a Tag Team Tables match. X-Pac performed a Super X-Factor through a table on Bubba to win the match.\n\n===Main event===\nIn the main event, [[Dwayne Johnson|The Rock]] defended the [[WWE Championship|WWF Championship]] against [[Triple H]] in a 60-minute Iron Man match with WWF Commissioner Shawn Michaels as the special guest referee. Rock performed a Rock bottom on Triple H to make the score 1-0. Triple H performed a Pedigree on Rock to make the score 1-1. Triple H pinned Rock with a Small Package to make the score 2-1. Triple H performed a Piledriver on Rock to make the score 3-1. Rock performed a DDT on Triple H to make the score 3-2. Triple H was disqualified for attacking Rock with a steel chair, making the score 3-3. Triple H pinned Rock using the ropes for leverage to make the score 4-3. Rock passed out to a Sleeper Hold by Triple H, making the score 5-3. Triple H was counted out after Rock performed a Pedigree on an announce table on Triple H, making the score 5-4. Rock performed a People's Elbow on Triple H to make the score 5-5. After Road Dogg and X-Pac interfered, [[The Undertaker]] returned and attacked Road Dogg, X-Pac, [[Shane McMahon]] and [[Vince McMahon]]. Undertaker attacked Triple H with a Chokeslam and a Tombstone Piledriver as the time limit expired. Rock was disqualified for Undertaker's interference, meaning Triple H won the match 6-5 and the title.\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe Rock continued his feud with Triple H, who now had to also contend with The Undertaker and, by association, [[Kane (wrestler)|Kane]]. This led to a six-man tag team match at [[King of the Ring (2000)|King of the Ring]] the next month featuring The Rock, The Undertaker, and Kane against Triple H, Vince McMahon, and Shane McMahon where if any member of Triple H's team was pinned, whoever scored the fall would win the WWF Championship. The Rock won the match for his team by pinning Vince McMahon.\n\nDX and the Dudley Boyz continued their feud at King of the Ring as well, with a Table/Dumpster match with the same teams. DX won the match, but Bubba Ray got his revenge on Tori by putting her through a table.\n\nLess than a week before King of the Ring, Chris Benoit would lose the Intercontinental Championship to Rikishi. Edge and Christian would lose the WWF Tag Team Championship to Too Cool. [[Crash Holly]] would regain the Hardcore Championship from [[Gerald Brisco]], but would lose it back to him right before King of the Ring. Brisco would lose the title to [[Pat Patterson (wrestler)|Pat Patterson]], starting a brief feud between the two.\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Results==\n{{Pro Wrestling results table\n|match1 = [[Too Cool]] ([[Grand Master Sexay]], [[Rikishi (wrestler)|Rikishi]] and [[Scotty 2 Hotty]]) defeated [[Team ECK]] ([[Edge (wrestler)|Edge]], [[Christian Cage|Christian]] and [[Kurt Angle]])\n|stip1  = [[Six-man tag team match]]\n|time1 = 09:46\n|match2 = [[Eddie Guerrero]] (c) (with [[Chyna]]) defeated [[Dean Malenko]] and [[Perry Saturn]] \n|stip2  = [[Triple threat match]] for the [[WWF European Championship]]\n|time2 = 07:57\n|match3 = [[Shane McMahon]] defeated [[Big Show]]\n|stip3  = [[Falls Count Anywhere match]]\n|time3 = 07:12\n|match4 = [[Chris Benoit]] (c) defeated [[Chris Jericho]]\n|stip4 = [[Submission match]] for the [[WWF Intercontinental Championship]]\n|time4 = 13:27\n|match5 = [[D-Generation X]] ([[Road Dogg]] and [[X-Pac]]) (with [[Tori (wrestler)|Tori]]) defeated [[The Dudley Boyz]] ([[Bubba Ray Dudley]] and [[D-Von Dudley]])\n|stip5 = [[Tag team match|Tag team]] [[Professional wrestling match types#Tables match|tables match]]\n|time5 = 10:55\n|match6 = [[Triple H]] (with [[Shane McMahon]], [[Stephanie McMahon-Helmsley]] and [[Mr. McMahon]]) defeated [[Dwayne Johnson|The Rock]] (c) 6\u20135\n|stip6  = 60-minute [[iron man match]] for the [[WWF Championship]] with [[Shawn Michaels]] as the [[Professional wrestling match types#Special referee|special guest referee]]\n|time6 = 1:00:00\n}}\n\n===Iron man match===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!'''Score'''\n!'''Point Winner'''\n!'''Decision'''\n!'''Notes'''\n!'''Time'''\n|-\n|0\u20131\n|The Rock\n|Pinfall\n|Pinfall after a Rock Bottom.\n\n|10:42\n|-\n|1\u20131\n|Triple H\n|Pinfall\n|Pinfall after a Pedigree\n|25:28\n|-\n|2\u20131\n|Triple H\n|Pinfall\n|Pinfall with an inside cradle\n|26:27\n|-\n|3\u20131\n|Triple H\n|Pinfall\n|Pinfall after a Piledriver\n|32:23\n|-\n|3\u20132\n|The Rock\n|Pinfall\n|Pinfall after a DDT\n|40:35\n|-\n|3\u20133\n|The Rock\n|Disqualification\n|Triple H was disqualified for attacking The Rock with a steel chair\n|43:43\n|-\n|4\u20133\n|Triple H\n|Pinfall\n|Pinfall using the ropes for leverage\n|4