pulation_metro = 231,891\n| population_metro_footnotes = \n| population_density_metro_km2 = \n| population_density_metro_sq_mi = \n| population_rank = \n| population_density_rank = \n| population_blank1_title = \n| population_blank1 = \n| population_density_blank1_km2 = \n| population_density_blank1_sq_mi = \n| population_blank2_title = \n| population_blank2 = \n| population_density_blank2_km2 = \n| population_density_blank2_sq_mi = \n| population_demonym = Champaignian\n| population_note = \n| demographics_type1 = \n| demographics1_footnotes = \n| demographics1_title1 = \n| demographics_type2 = \n| demographics2_footnotes = \n| demographics2_title1 = \n| demographics2_info1 = \n| timezone1 = [[Central Time Zone|CST]]\n| utc_offset1 = \u22126\n| timezone1_DST = [[Central Daylight Time|CDT]]\n| utc_offset1_DST = \u22125\n| timezone2 = \n| utc_offset2 = \n| timezone2_DST = \n| utc_offset2_DST = \n| postal_code_type = [[ZIP code]]s\n| postal_code = 61820\u201361822,<br/>61824\u201361826 (PO Box)\n| postal2_code_type = \n| postal2_code = \n| area_code = [[Area code 217|217]]\n| area_code_type = [[North American Numbering Plan|Area code]]\n| geocode = \n| iso_code = \n| blank_name_sec2 = \n| blank_info_sec2 = \n| blank1_name_sec2 = \n| blank1_info_sec2 = \n| etymology = \n| pushpin_label = \n| grid_name = \n| grid_position = \n| established_title4 = \n| established_date4 = \n| established_title5 = \n| established_date5 = \n| established_title6 = \n| established_date6 = \n| established_title7 = \n| established_date7 = \n| seat1_type = \n| seat1 = \n| area_metro_footnotes = \n| elevation_point = \n| elevation_max_m = \n| elevation_max_ft = \n| elevation_max_point = \n| elevation_max_rank = \n| elevation_min_point = \n| elevation_min_rank = \n| population_density = \n| demographics1_info1 = \n| blank_name = [[Federal Information Processing Standards|FIPS code]]\n| blank_info = 17-12385\n| blank1_name = \n| blank1_info = \n| blank2_name = \n| blank2_info = \n| blank2_name_sec2 = Wikimedia Commons\n| blank2_info_sec2 = \n| website = {{URL|www.champaignil.gov|champaignil.gov}}\n| footnotes = <ref name=\"gnis\">{{Cite GNIS|2393796|City of Champaign}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Champaign''' ({{IPAc-en|lang|\u02cc|\u0283|\u00e6|m|\u02c8|p|e\u026a|n|}}) is a city in [[Champaign County, Illinois]], United States. The city is {{convert|135|mi|0}} south of [[Chicago]], {{convert|124|mi|0}} west of [[Indianapolis, Indiana]], and {{convert|178|mi|0|abbr=on}} northeast of [[St. Louis, Missouri]]. The [[United States Census Bureau]] estimates the city was home to 88,029 people as of July 1, 2018.<ref name=\"factfinder2.census.gov\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|title=U.S. Census website|last=|first=|date=July 2017|website=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=1 June 2018}}</ref> Champaign is the [[List of cities in Illinois#Most populous places|tenth-most populous city]] in Illinois, and the state's fourth-most populous city outside the [[Chicago metropolitan area]]. It is included in the [[Champaign\u2013Urbana metropolitan area]].\n\nChampaign is notable for sharing the campus of the [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign]] with its sister city of [[Urbana, Illinois|Urbana]]. Champaign is also home to [[Parkland College]] which serves about 18,000 students during the academic year.<ref>[http://www.parkland.edu/about/quickfacts.aspx# Parkland College \u2013 About Us \u2013 Quick Facts] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130508084152/http://www.parkland.edu/about/quickfacts.aspx%23|date=May 8, 2013}}. Parkland.edu. Retrieved on 2013-08-17.</ref> Due to the university and a number of well known technology [[startup company|startup companies]], it is often referred to as the hub, or a significant landmark, of the [[Silicon Prairie]]. Champaign houses offices for the Fortune 500 companies [[Abbott Laboratories|Abbott]], [[Archer Daniels Midland]] (ADM), [[Caterpillar Inc.|Caterpillar]], [[John Deere]], [[Dow Chemical Company]], [[IBM]], and [[State Farm]].\n\n==History==\nChampaign was founded in 1855, when the [[Illinois Central Railroad]] laid its rail track two miles (3&nbsp;km) west of downtown Urbana. Originally called \"West Urbana\", it was renamed Champaign when it acquired a city charter in 1860. Both the city and county name were derived from [[Champaign County, Ohio]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ci.champaign.il.us/about-champaign/history/|title=City of Champaign official website \u2013 History |publisher=Ci.champaign.il.us|date=2013-01-24|accessdate=2013-04-08}}</ref>\n\n{{multiple image\n| align     = left\n| direction = horizontal\n| width     = <!-- Digits only; no \"px\" suffix, please -->\n\n| image1    = ChampaignCountyHistoricalMuseum 20080301 4255.jpg\n| width1    = 195\n| alt1      = \n| caption1  =\n\n| image2    = ChampaignCountyHistoricalMuseum 20080301 4261.jpg\n| width2    = 150\n| alt2      = \n| caption2  =\n\n| footer            = The [[Cattle Bank]] building, constructed in 1858, is the oldest surviving building in Champaign.\n| header_align      = <!-- left/right/center -->\n| footer_align      = center\n}}\nDuring February 1969, [[Carl Perkins]] joined with [[Bob Dylan]] to write the song \"Champaign, Illinois\", which Perkins released on his album ''On Top''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockabillyhall.com/CarlPerkins.html |title=RAB Hall of Fame: Carl Perkins |publisher=Rockabillyhall.com |date=|accessdate=2013-04-08}}</ref> The band [[Old 97's]] took another Bob Dylan song, \"[[Desolation Row]]\", and combined its melody with new lyrics to make a new song \"Champaign, Illinois\", which they released with Dylan's blessing on their 2010 album ''The Grand Theatre Volume One''. It achieved considerable popularity. The two \"Champaign, Illinois\" songs are not similar to each other, except that Bob Dylan was involved in both of them.\n\nOn September 22, 1985, Champaign hosted the first [[Farm Aid]] concert at the University of Illinois' [[Memorial Stadium (Champaign)|Memorial Stadium]]. The concert drew a crowd of 80,000 people and raised over $7 million for American family farmers.\n\nIn 2005, Champaign-Urbana (specifically the University of Illinois) was the location of the National [[Science Olympiad]] Tournament, attracting young scientists from all 50 states. The city also hosts the state Science Olympiad competition every year. The University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign once again hosted the National competition on May 20\u201322, 2010.\n\nIn 2013, Champaign was rated fifth best place in the United States for a healthy work-life balance.<ref>[http://www.nerdwallet.com/blog/2013/best-places-work-life-balance/ Best Places for Work-Life Balance]. Nerdwallet.com (2013-07-14). Retrieved on 2013-08-17.</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n\n===Location===\nAccording to the 2010 census, Champaign has a total area of {{convert|22.457|sqmi|sqkm|2}}, of which {{convert|22.43|sqmi|sqkm|2}} (or 99.88%) is land and {{convert|0.027|sqmi|sqkm|2}} (or 0.12%) is water.<ref name=\"census-g001\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/1600000US1712385\n  |title=G001 - Geographic Identifiers - 2010 Census Summary File 1\n  |accessdate=2015-12-25\n  |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]\n  |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213043436/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/G001/1600000US1712385\n  |archive-date=2020-02-13\n  |url-status=dead\n  }}</ref>\n\nChampaign is located on relatively high ground, providing sources to the [[Kaskaskia River]] to the west, and the [[Embarras River (Illinois)|Embarras River]] to the south.  Downtown Champaign drains into Boneyard Creek, which feeds the Saline Branch of the [[Salt Fork Vermilion River]].<ref name=\"usgs-topo-maps\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.mappingsupport.com/p/gmap4.php?ll=40.109317,-88.244614&z=14&t=t4&hillshade=0\n  |title=USGS Topo Maps}}</ref>\n\nChampaign shares a border with the neighboring city of [[Urbana, Illinois|Urbana]]; together they are home to the [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign|University of Illinois]]. Champaign, Urbana, and the bordering village of [[Savoy, Illinois|Savoy]] form the [[Champaign-Urbana Metropolitan Area]] also known as ''Champaign-Urbana''. It may also be colloquially known as the \"Twin Cities\" or ''[[Chambana]]''.{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}}\n\nThe following diagram represents localities within a {{convert|35|mi|km}} radius of Champaign.\n<div style=\"position: relative; float:left; width:500px;\">\n[[Image:Blank map.svg|400px|left|Neighboring localities]]\n{{Image label|x=0.5|y=0.5|scale=400|text=[[Image:Map pointer black.svg|20px|Champaign]]'''Champaign'''}}\n{{Image label|x=0.53|y=0.52|scale=400|text=[[Image:Dot-yellow.svg|20px|18px|Locality with 41,250 inhabitants (2010).]] <small>[[Urbana, Illinois|Urbana]] (0 mi)</small>}}\n{{Image label|x=0.495|y=0.565|scale=400|text=[[Image:Small-city-symbol.svg|16px|Locality with 7,280 inhabitants (2010).]] <small>[[Savoy, Illinois|Savoy]] (4 mi)</small>}}\n{{Image label|x=0.40|y=0.42|scale=400|text=[[Image:Small-city-symbol.svg|16px|Locality with 7,258 inhabitants (2010).]] <small>[[Mahomet, Illinois|Mahomet]] (10 mi)</small>}}\n{{Image label|x=0.225|y=0.585|scale=400|text=[[Image:Small-city-symbol.svg|16px|Locality with 5,374 inhabitants (2009).]] <small>[[Monticello, Illinois|Monticello]] (22 mi)</small>}}\n{{Image label|x=0.475|y=0.80|scale=400|text=[[Image:Small-city-symbol.svg|14px|Locality with 4,480 inhabitants (2010).]] <small>[[Tuscola, Illinois|Tuscola]] (23 mi)</small>}}\n{{Image label|x=0.96|y=0.484|scale=400|text=[[Image:Dot-yellow.svg|16px|Locality with 33,027 inhabitants (2010).]] <small>[[Danville, Illinois|Danville]] (35 mi)</small>}}\n{{Image label|x=0.46|y=0.90|scale=400|text=[[Image:Small-city-symbol.svg|12px|Locality with 2,916 inhabitants (2010).]] <small>[[Arcola, Illinois|Arcola]] (30 mi)</small>}}\n{{Image label|x=0.57|y=0.3|scale=400|text=[[Image:Small-city-symbol.svg|18px|Locality with 12,491 inhabitants (2010).]] <small>[[Rantoul, Illinois|Rantoul]] (15 mi)</small>}}\n{{Image label|x=0.60|y=0.18|scale=400|text=[[Image:Small-city-symbol.svg|14px|Locality with 4,473 inhabitants (2010).]] <small>[[Paxton, Illinois|Paxton]] (25 mi)</small>}}\n{{Image label|x=0.265|y=0.155|scale=400|text=[[Image:Small-city-symbol.svg|12px|Locality with 3,407 inhabitants (2010).]] <small>[[Gibson City, Illinois|Gibson City]] (30 mi)</small>}}\n</div>{{clear|left}}\n\n===Climate===\nThe city has a [[humid continental climate]], typical of the Midwestern United States, with hot summers and cold, moderately snowy winters. Temperatures exceed 90&nbsp;\u00b0F (32.2&nbsp;\u00b0C) on an average of 24 days per year, and typically fall below 0&nbsp;\u00b0F (\u221217.8&nbsp;\u00b0C) on six nights annually.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather.php3?s=047811&refer=&cityname=Champaign-Illinois-United-States-of-America |title=Weatherbase: Historical Weather for Champaign, Illinois, United States of America \u2013 Travel, Vacation and Reference Information |publisher=Canty and Associates LLC |date=|accessdate=2011-09-19}}</ref> The record high temperature in Champaign was 109&nbsp;\u00b0F (42.8&nbsp;\u00b0C) in 1954, and the record low was \u221225&nbsp;\u00b0F (\u221231.7&nbsp;\u00b0C), recorded on four separate occasions \u2212 in 1899, 1905, 1994 and 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.isws.illinois.edu/atmos/statecli/cuweather/cu-averages.htm |title=Averages and Records for Champaign-Urbana Illinois |publisher=Illinois State Water Survey |date=|accessdate=2011-09-29}}</ref>\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Champaign, Illinois\n|single line = Y\n|Jan record high F = 70\n|Feb record high F = 72\n|Mar record high F = 85\n|Apr record high F = 91\n|May record high F = 97\n|Jun record high F = 103\n|Jul record high F = 109\n|Aug record high F = 102\n|Sep record high F = 101\n|Oct record high F = 93\n|Nov record high F = 80\n|D