{"title_page": "Richard Brooke (Norton)", "text_new": ":''For later members of this family, many of whom were named Richard, see [[Brooke baronets#Brooke of Norton, Cheshire (England 12 December 1662)|Brooke of Norton, Cheshire]]''\n\n'''Richard Brooke''' (died 1569) bought the [[Manorialism|manor]] of [[Norton, Runcorn|Norton]], near [[Runcorn]], [[Cheshire]] from [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]] in 1545 following the [[dissolution of the monasteries]].  The manor included the former monastery of [[Norton Priory]] and also the settlements of Norton, Stockham, Acton Grange and Aston Grange in [[Cheshire]] and [[Cuerdley]] in [[Lancashire]].<ref name=\"Ormerod\">{{Citation |last=Ormerod |first=George |authorlink=George Ormerod |coauthors= |editor= T. Helsby|others= |title=History of the County Palatine and City of Chester  |edition=2nd  |year=1882 |publisher= Routledge|location= London |isbn= |doi= |id= |volume = i |page = 680 |oclc = 1726839}}</ref>\n\nRichard Brooke was the younger son of Thomas Brooke of Leighton in [[Nantwich]] [[Hundred (country subdivision)|Hundred]].  In his earlier life he had been a soldier and he was admitted as a [[Knights Hospitaller|Knight of Malta]] in 1531. He then became Commander of Mount St. John in [[Cleveland, England|Cleveland]]. After the suppression of the Order by [[Henry_VIII_of_England|Henry VIII]] circa 1542, he was relieved of his religious vows and held the office of Vice-Admiral of England. In May 1544 he served in Lord Hertford's army in Scotland which [[Burning of Edinburgh|sacked and burnt Edinburgh]]. Brooke captured and destroyed the fortress on the island of [[Inchgarvie]] in the ''[[List of early warships of the English navy|Galley Subtile]]'' on 6 May 1544.<ref>'Late Expedition in Scotland, 1544', in ''Tudor Tracts'' (London, 1903), 44: ''Letters & Papers, Henry VIII'', vol. 19 part 1 (London, 1908), no. 472.</ref>\n\nFollowing the dissolution of the monasteries, the abbey of Norton Priory was made inhospitable.<ref name=\"Starkey\">{{Citation | last =Starkey | first =H. F. | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =Old Runcorn |edition= | publisher =Halton Borough Council | year =1990 | location =Halton  | page =39 | url = | doi = | id = | isbn = }}</ref>  Having bought the property, it seems that Brooke did not have the resources necessary to build an expensive house and therefore he modified the west range of the abbey as his residence, while the [[cloister]] became a rubbish dump.<ref>{{Citation| last =Greene | first =Patrick | authorlink = J. Patrick Greene  | title =Norton Priory: The archaeology of a medieval religious house |edition= | publisher =[[Cambridge University Press]] | year =1989 | location =Cambridge | pages =150\u2013151 | isbn =0-521-33054-8 }}</ref> The remaining buildings and the church were demolished and sold for building stone.<ref name=\"Starkey\"/>\n\nFollowing the accession of [[Mary I of England|Queen Mary]] to the throne in 1553, Brooke assisted [[Cardinal Pole|Reginald Pole]] in the re-establishment of the [[Sovereign Military Order of Malta|Order of St John]] in England.<ref>{{Citation | last = Bostock | first = Tony | author-link = | publication-date = 2009 | date = | year = 2009 | title = Sir Oliver Starkey, Knight of Malta | periodical = Cheshire History | series = | publication-place = Chester | place = | page = 37 | publisher = Cheshire Local History Association | volume = 49 | issue = |ISSN = 0141-8696}}</ref>  Brooke was [[Sheriff]] of Cheshire in 1563.  He was succeeded at Norton Priory by his eldest son, Thomas.<ref name=\"Ormerod\"/>\n\n==Family==\nHe married Christian, daughter of John Carew of Haccombe in [[Devon]], with whom he had three sons.<ref name=\"Ormerod\"/>\n\nRichard Brooke's daughter Christiane married Richard Grosvenor of Eaton and was the mother of [[Sir Richard Grosvenor, 1st Baronet]], the ancestor of the [[Duke of Westminster|Dukes of Westminster]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brooke, Richard}}\n[[Category:1569 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Runcorn]]\n[[Category:People of the Tudor period]]\n[[Category:Knights of Malta]]\n[[Category:English admirals]]\n[[Category:16th-century English people]]\n[[Category:16th-century Royal Navy personnel]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n", "text_old": ":''For later members of this family, many of whom were named Richard, see [[Brooke baronets#Brooke of Norton, Cheshire (England 12 December 1662)|Brooke of Norton, Cheshire]]''\n\n'''Richard Brooke''' (died 1569) bought the [[Manorialism|manor]] of [[Norton, Runcorn|Norton]], near [[Runcorn]], [[Cheshire]] from [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]] in 1545 following the [[dissolution of the monasteries]].  The manor included the former monastery of [[Norton Priory]] and also the settlements of Norton, Stockham, Acton Grange and Aston Grange in [[Cheshire]] and [[Cuerdley]] in [[Lancashire]].<ref name=\"Ormerod\">{{Citation |last=Ormerod |first=George |authorlink=George Ormerod |coauthors= |editor= T. Helsby|others= |title=History of the County Palatine and City of Chester  |edition=2nd  |year=1882 |publisher= Routledge|location= London |isbn= |doi= |id= |volume = i |page = 680 |oclc = 1726839}}</ref>\n\nRichard Brooke was the younger son of Thomas Brooke of Leighton in [[Nantwich]] [[Hundred (country subdivision)|Hundred]].  In his earlier life he had been a soldier and he was admitted as a [[Knights Hospitaller|Knight of Malta]] in 1531. He then became Commander of Mount St. John in [[Cleveland, England|Cleveland]]. After the suppression of the Order by [[Henry_VIII_of_England|Henry VIII]] circa 1542, he was relieved of his religious vows and held the office of Vice-Admiral of England. In May 1544 he served in Lord Hertford's army in Scotland which [[Burning of Edinburgh|sacked and burnt Edinburgh]]. Brooke captured and destroyed the fortress on the island of [[Inchgarvie]] in the ''[[Galley Subtile]]'' on 6 May 1544.<ref>'Late Expedition in Scotland, 1544', in ''Tudor Tracts'' (London, 1903), 44: ''Letters & Papers, Henry VIII'', vol. 19 part 1 (London, 1908), no. 472.</ref>\n\nFollowing the dissolution of the monasteries, the abbey of Norton Priory was made inhospitable.<ref name=\"Starkey\">{{Citation | last =Starkey | first =H. F. | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =Old Runcorn |edition= | publisher =Halton Borough Council | year =1990 | location =Halton  | page =39 | url = | doi = | id = | isbn = }}</ref>  Having bought the property, it seems that Brooke did not have the resources necessary to build an expensive house and therefore he modified the west range of the abbey as his residence, while the [[cloister]] became a rubbish dump.<ref>{{Citation| last =Greene | first =Patrick | authorlink = J. Patrick Greene  | title =Norton Priory: The archaeology of a medieval religious house |edition= | publisher =[[Cambridge University Press]] | year =1989 | location =Cambridge | pages =150\u2013151 | isbn =0-521-33054-8 }}</ref> The remaining buildings and the church were demolished and sold for building stone.<ref name=\"Starkey\"/>\n\nFollowing the accession of [[Mary I of England|Queen Mary]] to the throne in 1553, Brooke assisted [[Cardinal Pole|Reginald Pole]] in the re-establishment of the [[Sovereign Military Order of Malta|Order of St John]] in England.<ref>{{Citation | last = Bostock | first = Tony | author-link = | publication-date = 2009 | date = | year = 2009 | title = Sir Oliver Starkey, Knight of Malta | periodical = Cheshire History | series = | publication-place = Chester | place = | page = 37 | publisher = Cheshire Local History Association | volume = 49 | issue = |ISSN = 0141-8696}}</ref>  Brooke was [[Sheriff]] of Cheshire in 1563.  He was succeeded at Norton Priory by his eldest son, Thomas.<ref name=\"Ormerod\"/>\n\n==Family==\nHe married Christian, daughter of John Carew of Haccombe in [[Devon]], with whom he had three sons.<ref name=\"Ormerod\"/>\n\nRichard Brooke's daughter Christiane married Richard Grosvenor of Eaton and was the mother of [[Sir Richard Grosvenor, 1st Baronet]], the ancestor of the [[Duke of Westminster|Dukes of Westminster]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brooke, Richard}}\n[[Category:1569 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Runcorn]]\n[[Category:People of the Tudor period]]\n[[Category:Knights of Malta]]\n[[Category:English admirals]]\n[[Category:16th-century English people]]\n[[Category:16th-century Royal Navy personnel]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Brooke_(Norton)"}
